<!DOCTYPE html>
<%# 2026-05-19 — single dark theme. The legacy localStorage-driven
    light/dark toggle (`pito-theme` key + inline bootstrap script +
    `theme` Stimulus controller + `data-theme` html attribute) was
    removed. CSS now ships a single (dark) palette; no per-user
    preference is read or persisted. %>
<html data-theme="dark">
  <head>
    <%# Title is built with safe_join rather than string interpolation so
        HTML entities embedded in the page title (such as apostrophe
        entities from a project name) survive untouched. A plain yield
        plus " ~ pito" interpolation would drop the SafeBuffer status
        and re-escape entities into the browser tab; safe_join keeps
        the SafeBuffer contract end-to-end. (Note: this comment used
        to mention an ERB output tag literal, which contained the
        sequence that closes a comment block, and that broke document
        parsing — see fix on 2026-05-06.) %>
    <title><%= content_for?(:title) ? safe_join([yield(:title), " ~ pito"]) : "pito ~ best YouTube tool" %></title>
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1">
    <meta name="application-name" content="pito">
    <meta name="turbo-refresh-method" content="morph">
    <meta name="turbo-refresh-scroll" content="preserve">
    <%= csrf_meta_tags %>
    <%= csp_meta_tag %>

    <%# ADR 0018 — Action bus meta tag. Carries every registered
        `Pito::Action`'s JS-readable subset (name, path, method,
        confirmation, i18n labels, cable_panel) so `window.Pito.dispatchAction`
        can resolve actions without round-tripping the server. Turbo's
        head-merge (`mergeProvisionalElements` / `isEqualNode`) keeps this
        node identical across navigations as long as the route table is
        unchanged. Updates ship via a head re-render whenever the
        registry mutates. %>
    <meta name="pito-actions" content="<%= Pito::ActionRegistry.all.to_h { |a| [a.name.to_s, a.to_h] }.to_json %>">

    <%# 2026-05-25 — Screen-scoped action catalog for the `:` palette.
        Carries only the actions whose scope is :global OR matches the
        current screen (home / videos / games). This is the palette's
        pre-filtered action bus catalog; it prevents cross-screen noise
        (e.g. "reindex Meilisearch" must not appear on /videos or /games).
        Turbo's head-merge swaps this tag on navigation so the palette
        catalog updates correctly when moving between screens.
        See `ApplicationHelper#pito_screen_actions_json` for the server-side
        filter logic and `Pito::ActionRegistry.for_screen` for the registry
        query. %>
    <meta name="pito-screen-actions" content="<%= pito_screen_actions_json %>">

    <%# Phase 1D (2026-05-24 sync-rebuild) — serialized i18n strings for
        ephemeral TST notices. The JS notice emitters (sync toggles, etc.)
        read this meta and dispatch `tui:notice` events with the
        ready-to-display string. Same YAML feeds the future Rust TUI
        client; the JS path stays free of an in-browser i18n runtime. %>
    <meta name="pito-notices" content="<%= I18n.t('tui.notices').to_json %>">

    <%# 2026-05-20 — section-accent meta tag. The `<body data-section>`
        attribute below is the canonical signal for the Dracula section-
        variant accent CSS cascade, but Turbo Drive replaces body
        CONTENT on navigation without re-applying body element
        ATTRIBUTES — meaning `data-section` stayed at the first
        page's value across all subsequent Turbo navigations. Same
        head-merge rationale as `pito-enroll-totp-gate` and the
        keybindings JSON: Turbo's `mergeProvisionalElements` diffs
        head children and swaps mismatched meta tags, so this tag's
        `content` reliably reflects the freshly-loaded page. A tiny
        JS shim in `application.js` listens for `turbo:load` /
        `turbo:render` / `DOMContentLoaded` and copies the meta
        value to `document.body.dataset.section` after each
        navigation. The server-side `<body data-section="...">`
        below is preserved so the initial paint still carries the
        correct accent before any JS runs. The `pito:` prefix
        avoids collision with any HTML standard `<meta name="section">`
        semantic. %>
    <meta name="pito:section" content="<%= current_section %>">

    <%# Z1 (2026-05-25) — pito-enroll-totp-gate meta tag removed.
        Enrollment is now Rake-only (`bin/rails pito:auth:enroll`).
        There is no web enrollment flow and no "user with TOTP not yet
        configured" state. The gate machinery and all Current.user
        references here are gone. %>

    <%# Unified keybindings schema — single source of truth for the
        leader-menu popup AND the Rust pito CLI's leader overlay,
        sourced from `config/keybindings.yml`. Mounted in `<head>`
        so Turbo Drive's head-merge preserves the tag across page
        navigations (same `isEqualNode` rationale that anchors the
        `pito-enroll-totp-gate` meta tag above). The Stimulus
        `leader-menu` + `flat-key` controllers parse the JSON
        lazily on each keystroke via `document.getElementById`,
        so the head-resident tag is always findable regardless of
        connect-time DOM ordering.

        `<script type="application/json">` is non-executable; the
        browser hands the literal bytes to `JSON.parse` when the
        controllers read it, so head-position is safe (no inline
        execution). The schema itself is statically generated from
        the YAML at boot and contains no user input. %>
    <script type="application/json" id="pito-keybindings"><%= keybindings_as_json %></script>

    <%= yield :head %>

    <%# Phase 7.5 — MCP custom-connector icon discovery. Claude.ai's
        connector probe path isn't documented; we shotgun every
        reasonable surface so whichever path Claude actually checks
        resolves to the Pito logo. The legacy `public/Pito.png`
        single-source mark was retired 2026-05-19 in favor of the
        Real Favicon Generator multi-size set in `public/`. Surfaces
        covered:
          - `<link rel="icon" sizes=...>` — full multi-size favicon
            set (16/32/48/96/192/256) generated by the Real Favicon
            Generator and placed in `public/`. Browsers pick the
            best fit; legacy browsers fall back to the generic
            `<link rel="icon" href="/favicon-32x32.png">` at the end.
          - `<link rel="apple-touch-icon">` (bare + 180x180) —
            Apple convention. Bare points to the bundled
            `/apple-touch-icon.png` (180x180); the 180x180 variant
            stays explicit for clients that filter by size.
          - `<meta property="og:*">` — Open Graph image, absolute
            URL (required by the OG spec). Points at
            `/android-chrome-512x512.png` (largest available, best
            for Twitter / OG previews).
          - `<link rel="manifest">` — web app manifest at
            `/manifest.json` (pito-customized; lists
            `/android-chrome-512x512.png` as the install icon).
          - `/favicon.ico` route alias (`config/routes.rb`) → 301 to
            `/favicon-32x32.png` for clients that ONLY check `.ico`.
            No `public/favicon.ico` file exists, so the route hits.
          - Fallback `<link rel="icon" href="/favicon-32x32.png">`
            keeps non-MCP / non-sized-aware clients anchored on a
            single canonical asset.
        Per-surface size picks live in the LOGO-RAILS dispatch
        (2026-05-19): header logo + footer logo use
        `/favicon-64x64.png`, About modal uses `/favicon-128x128.png`,
        OAuth / MCP `logo_uri` uses `/android-chrome-192x192.png`. %>
    <%# 2026-05-19 — `?v=2` cache-bust on every favicon URL. favicons2.zip
        overwrote the bytes in /public but browsers (and PWA install hosts,
        OG scrapers) were still serving the prior assets from cache. The
        query string forces a fresh fetch on the next hard-refresh; next
        deploy that updates the favicon set bumps `?v=3` etc. The manifest
        itself stays unsuffixed — it's parsed fresh on PWA install — but
        the icon entries inside `public/manifest.json` carry their own
        `?v=2` so install-time icon fetches also cache-miss. %>
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="16x16" href="/favicon-16x16.png?v=2">
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="32x32" href="/favicon-32x32.png?v=2">
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="48x48" href="/favicon-48x48.png?v=2">
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="96x96" href="/favicon-96x96.png?v=2">
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="192x192" href="/android-chrome-192x192.png?v=2">
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="256x256" href="/favicon-256x256.png?v=2">
    <link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/apple-touch-icon.png?v=2">
    <link rel="apple-touch-icon" sizes="180x180" href="/apple-touch-icon.png?v=2">
    <link rel="icon" href="/favicon-32x32.png?v=2" type="image/png">
    <link rel="manifest" href="/manifest.json">
    <meta name="theme-color" content="#ffffff">
    <meta property="og:title" content="pito">
    <meta property="og:description" content="best YouTube tool">
    <meta property="og:image" content="https://app.pitomd.com/android-chrome-512x512.png?v=2">

    <%= stylesheet_link_tag :app, "data-turbo-track": "reload" %>
    <%= javascript_importmap_tags %>
  </head>

  <%# Phase 29 (settings refactor) — keyboard navigation is always on.
      The master toggle pane was dropped; the keyboard Stimulus
      controller no longer reads `data-keyboard-navigation-enabled` and
      registers its keydown listener unconditionally.

      Phase 26 — 01a. Mount the `timezone-detect` Stimulus controller on
      `<body>`. Authenticated layouts render the user's stored zone in
      `data-timezone-detect-stored-value`; on the "Etc/UTC" sentinel
      the controller silently PATCHes the browser-detected zone to
      `/settings/time_zone`. The data-attribute is omitted on
      unauthenticated screens (login form, OAuth consent) so the
      controller bails immediately. %>
  <%# 2026-05-16 — mandatory-2FA gate signal moved to a `<meta>` tag
      in `<head>` (see the head block above for the full rationale).
      The keydown handlers in `keyboard` and `leader-menu` (2026-05-17
      — `theme` no longer mounts a keydown listener) read the meta
      tag live on every keypress, so no per-body script, attribute,
      or controller `connect()` cache is needed here. %>
  <%# 2026-05-19 — `data-section` drives the Dracula section-variant
      accent system. ApplicationHelper#current_section maps the current
      controller_path to one of four buckets ("home", "channels",
      "games", "settings"); CSS in app/assets/tailwind/application.css
      reads the attribute and flips `--color-section-accent` (and the
      derived `--color-bg` + `--color-link` palette) per section.
      Modals reset the accent back to Dracula Purple inside the
      `dialog { ... }` block so modal chrome stays consistent
      regardless of which page opened them. %>
  <%# 2026-05-20 — Per-section bg + accent are computed in Ruby
      (`Pito::Theme::Sections`) and inlined here so the cascade uses
      single-source-of-truth values that are specced. The inline
      `--section-accent` CSS var still drives every downstream
      `color-mix(--section-accent, X%, ...)` token (chip bg, focus
      ring, pane border) in `app/assets/tailwind/application.css`; we
      only replaced the cascade SOURCE, not the cascade itself. The
      `background` inline overrides any prior body bg fallback so the
      Ruby-picked literal hex paints the canvas. %>
  <%# Z3 (2026-05-25) — `data-tui-authenticated` stamps the auth state on body
      so the `tui-panel-cable` Stimulus controller can skip cable subscriptions
      when the session is absent. "yes" / "no" per the project boundary convention.
      On successful POST /login, SessionsController redirects to root_path (full
      reload), which re-renders this attribute as "yes" so panels subscribe
      naturally without any in-place JS event. %>
  <body data-section="<%= current_section %>"
        data-tui-authenticated="<%= Current.session.present? ? "yes" : "no" %>"
        style="--section-accent: <%= pito_section_accent %>; --color-section-accent: <%= pito_section_accent %>; background: <%= pito_section_bg %>;"
        data-controller="keyboard notifications-modal tui-leader-menu flat-key timezone-detect webhook-help-modal dialog-scroll-lock sortable-keys tui-cursor tui-panel-nav"
        <%# `data-keybindings-page-key` exposes the YAML key (e.g.
            `games_index`, `games_show`, `bundles_show`, `default`,
            or `nil` for deny-listed pages like /settings) so the
            `leader-menu` Stimulus controller can render the per-page
            action rows in the popup's top section. Resolved by
            `KeybindingsHelper#keybindings_page_key`; the same helper
            powers `KeybindingsReferenceComponent`. Absent attribute
            (nil page key) = no page-actions section. %>
        <% if (kb_page_key = keybindings_page_key) %>data-keybindings-page-key="<%= kb_page_key %>"<% end %>
        <% if Current.session.present? %>data-timezone-detect-url-value="<%= settings_time_zone_path %>"
        data-timezone-detect-csrf-value="<%= form_authenticity_token %>"<% end %>>
    <%# FB-81 page-load splash REMOVED. Existed only to mask the FOUT
        moment during the font swap. System-mono-only renders with no
        font swap to mask, no splash needed. Element, Stimulus controller,
        and CSS rules all deleted together. %>
<%# Beta 4 — Phase F1 Lane D (2026-05-20). The legacy bracketed-nav
        header (`[home][calendar] · [channels][videos] · [projects][games] ·
        [notifications]  <spacer>  [settings][_]`) was replaced by the
        TUI-flavoured `Tui::TopStatusBarComponent` — a single status bar
        that surfaces version + section + optional page tail on the
        left, and sync state + Sidekiq queue depths + live clock on the
        right. The component subscribes to the `pito:status_bar` cable
        channel (ADR 0017, Lane A's `StatusBarChannel` +
        `StatusBarBroadcastMiddleware`) via the `tui-status-bar`
        Stimulus controller (Lane C). The `<header>` wrapper stays so
        sticky-positioning + `:hide_chrome` chrome suppression keep
        working unchanged.
        The `unless content_for?(:hide_chrome)` gate still hides the
        status bar on auth screens (login, OAuth consent, TOTP
        enrollment gate) just like the old navbar — only the inner
        component is swapped.
        The notifications-badge live-update mount (`turbo_stream_from
        "notifications_badge"` + `render "notifications/badge"`) was
        dropped along with the bracketed nav — the badge partial spec
        + the standalone /notifications page mounts still cover the
        partial; the layout-level live-update will return when
        /notifications comes back into scope. %>
    <%# FB-121 (2026-05-21) — TST height parity with BST. BST is
        4px top + 13px content + 4px bottom + 1px border-top = 22px.
        TST has its `border-bottom` neutralized by `body > header` rule
        in application.css (FB-23 dropped the hairline). To match
        22px the asymmetric padding splits the missing 1px border into
        an extra row of top padding: 5px + 13px + 4px + 0 = 22px. %>
    <header style="position: sticky; top: 0; left: 0; right: 0; background: var(--color-bg); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding: 5px 12px 4px 12px; z-index: 100;">
      <% unless content_for?(:hide_chrome) %>
        <%= render Tui::TopStatusBarComponent.new(
              section: current_section,
              version: pito_version
            ) %>
      <% end %>
    </header>

    <%# 2026-05-25 — legacy flash_toasts removed. Auth dialog renders the
        login error inline via Tui::HintComponent(severity: :danger). %>

    <%# 2026-05-19 — header is now `position: sticky` (was `fixed`) so the
        outer `padding-top: 32px` wrapper that compensated for the
        out-of-flow fixed header has been dropped. Sticky leaves the header
        in document flow so the main block sits naturally below it without
        any compensating gap.
        2026-05-20 — main side-padding trimmed from 12px → 6px so the
        `.pito-workspace` width-tiling grid (ADR 0016) reaches closer to
        the literal viewport edge.
        2026-05-20 (FB-17) — chrome-to-content gaps tightened to 6px top
        and 6px bottom (was 16px / 8px). The TUI density brief calls for
        Excel-sheet rhythm — the first pane row sits flush under the
        status bar, the bottom status bar hugs the last pane row. Side
        padding stays at 6px. %>
    <main id="pito-main-scroll" style="padding: 6px 6px;">
      <% if content_for?(:breadcrumbs) %>
        <nav class="dot-list" style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><%= yield :breadcrumbs %><% if content_for?(:breadcrumb_actions) %><%= yield :breadcrumb_actions %><% end %></nav>
      <% end %>
      <%= yield %>
    </main>

    <%# Z3 (2026-05-25) — Auth dialog overlay. Renders unconditionally when
        Current.session is nil so the root layout always serves. The dialog
        sits above all panel chrome via z-index 1000. Panels render their
        chrome skeleton but gate their body content via `tui_authenticated?`.
        On successful POST /login, the controller redirects to root_path so
        a full reload re-renders this without the dialog and panels show live data. %>
    <% unless Current.session.present? %>
      <%= render Pito::AuthDialogComponent.new %>
    <% end %>

    <%# Page-level scroll indicator — lives OUTSIDE <main> so <main>'s
        overflow-y: auto cannot clip the right-edge glyphs. Fixed-positioned
        against the viewport between TST (22px) + BST (22px). The Stimulus
        controller resolves its scroll source via the `source` value
        (CSS selector). %>
    <div class="tui-page-scroll-indicator"
         data-controller="tui-scroll-indicator"
         data-tui-scroll-indicator-axis-value="vertical"
         data-tui-scroll-indicator-source-value="#pito-main-scroll">
      <%= render Tui::ScrollIndicatorComponent.new(axis: :vertical) %>
    </div>

    <%# Beta 4 — Phase F1 (2026-05-20). The legacy centered copyright
        footer was replaced by `Tui::BottomStatusBarComponent` — a sticky
        TUI-flavoured status line that surfaces the current input mode
        (normal/command/search), the 8 top-level section links (with the
        active section bolded and accented via the `--section-accent`
        cascade), and the `?` help / `:` command keybinding hints. The
        copyright + version metadata still lives in
        `Tui::AboutDialogComponent` (opened via `space a` / `:about` command
        leader path), so removing the footer copyright did not orphan
        that information.
        Wired here unconditionally — the bar shows on every page that
        renders the layout, including auth screens, so the section + mode
        signals are visible at all times. %>
    <%# FB-170 (2026-05-21) — V6 `:command` palette. Pinned 22px above
        the BST via `position: fixed`. Hidden by default; the
        `tui-command-palette` Stimulus controller listens for `:` at
        document level (when no input has focus and no dialog is open)
        and shows the palette. Commands are sourced from
        `Tui::CommandRegistry.commands_for(controller_name)` — every
        screen gets the global verbs; screens with a registered
        `Tui::ScreenCommands::<Name>` module also get the screen-scoped
        commands stacked on top. %>
    <%= render Tui::CommandPaletteComponent.new(
          commands: Tui::CommandRegistry.commands_for(controller_name)
        ) %>

    <%= render Tui::BottomStatusBarComponent.new(current_section: current_section) %>

    <%# 2026-05-16 — the legacy keyboard-shortcuts help modal that
        used to mount here was retired. Keyboard discovery now lives
        exclusively in the leader-menu popup (`[_]` link in the
        navbar, immediately after `[settings]` — relocated from the
        footer on 2026-05-18 — plus SPACE keypress); the `?`
        keybinding and the `KeyboardShortcutsModalComponent` are gone. %>

    <%# D9 (2026-05-22). TUI help dialog (`Tui::HelpDialogComponent`) —
        a `<dialog>`-backed which-key style dialog listing every top-level
        pito keybinding (global flat keys, section nav, panel nav, mode,
        session). Opened by the `?` flat-key (the `tui-help-dialog`
        Stimulus controller intercepts `?` at document level) and closed
        by Esc or another `?` toggle. Mounted FIRST in the dialog pile so
        document order mirrors usage frequency. Replaces the retired
        `Tui::HelpOverlayComponent`. %>
    <%= render Tui::HelpDialogComponent.new %>

    <%# Phase 2A (2026-05-23) — viewport size-guard dialog. pito locks
        the body to `min-width: 1280px` / `min-height: 800px` (see
        `app/assets/tailwind/application.css`); the
        `tui-size-guard` Stimulus controller listens to window resize
        events and shows this dialog when the viewport falls below
        threshold. Renders once globally so every screen shares the
        guard. %>
    <%= render Tui::SizeGuardDialogComponent.new %>

    <%# Phase 37 (2026-05-19) — "Everywhere" omnisearch modal. Opened
        by the `/` flat-key on every page (per `config/keybindings.yml`
        `flat.items`) AND by the `space /` leader path on neutral
        pages (the `search_placeholder` YAML token in `page_actions:`
        resolves through `leader_menu_controller.openGlobalSearch()`
        to this same dialog). Replaces the prior `shared/_search_modal`
        ("search videos…" placeholder) that used to render here — the
        layout no longer mounts that legacy modal so only ONE `/`-
        targeted dialog exists on the page. Backed by
        `EverywhereSearchController#show` (`/search/everywhere`) and
        rendered via `Search::EverywhereResultsComponent`. The
        `current_path:` arg drives section ordering inside the
        results component (channels-first on `/channels*`, games-first
        on `/games*`, default order elsewhere). %>
    <%= render Search::EverywhereModalComponent.new(
          dialog_id: "omnisearch-modal-everywhere",
          url: everywhere_search_path,
          current_path: request.path
        ) %>

    <%# D9 (2026-05-22) — layout-level about dialog
        (`Tui::AboutDialogComponent`). Dialog id `about-dialog` matches
        the `space a` leader path target in `config/keybindings.yml` and
        the `:about` command target in `Tui::CommandRegistry`. Renders
        the identity card (name + version + license + source + commit +
        contact + env + copyright). Replaces the retired
        `AboutModalComponent`. %>
    <%= render Tui::AboutDialogComponent.new %>

    <%# Global IGDB-search modal — opened by the `[+]` bracketed link
        in the `/games` chrome (2026-05-17 the global `i` keybind was
        removed in the legacy-keyboard-shortcut sweep). Submits the
        typed query to `GamesController#search` (existing
        `/games/search`); the results render inside the modal's Turbo
        Frame and offer `[add]` (new) or `[update]` (existing-game
        overwrite via the shared overwrite-confirmation modal). %>
    <%= render "shared/igdb_search_modal" %>

    <%# Reusable overwrite-confirmation modal — opened by
        `data-action="click->modal-trigger#open"` from any
        `[update]` / `[resync]` link that wants to gate the
        IGDB-overwrite warning. The form action is set on the
        triggering link via the `igdb-overwrite-confirm`
        Stimulus controller's `pathValue`, so the same dialog
        body serves every game id. %>
    <%= render "shared/igdb_overwrite_modal" %>

    <%# Notifications modal — opened by the navbar `[notifications]`
        link (`data-action="click->notifications-modal#open"`). The
        modal loads `/notifications?modal=yes` into its Turbo Frame
        so the full inbox (heading, cleanup caption, filter chip,
        list, bulk actions, dynamic mark-button, nested detail
        modal) renders inside the dialog. The standalone
        `/notifications` page still serves direct URLs for JS-off
        fallback. %>
    <%= render "shared/notifications_modal" %>

    <%# Phase 26 — 01d. Webhook help modal — opened by the `[help]`
        link in the Settings Slack + Discord panes
        (`data-action="click->webhook-help-modal#open"` with a
        provider param). The modal loads
        `/settings/webhooks/help/<provider>` into its Turbo Frame and
        renders the Markdown guide inside the dialog. The guides
        live as on-disk `.md` files under
        `app/views/settings/webhooks/help/` and are rendered
        server-side via `ApplicationHelper#render_markdown`
        (Commonmarker). %>
    <%= render "shared/webhook_help_modal" %>

    <%# 2026-05-11 — Layout-level TOTP verification modal. Replaces
        the inline `2FA code` text inputs the YouTube / Voyage /
        Discord / Slack settings panes used to render. Per-form
        `totp-modal` controllers intercept the submit of a gated
        form and hand control to this dialog's `totp-modal-dialog`
        controller; on `[confirm]` the dialog injects a hidden
        `totp_code` input into the pending form and re-submits. The
        partial only renders when an authenticated user is present
        — there is no surface for the modal on the login / OAuth
        consent screens. %>
    <% if Current.session.present? %>
      <%= render "shared/totp_verification_modal" %>
    <% end %>

    <%# 2026-05-19 — keybindings schema `<script id="pito-keybindings">`
        tag moved to `<head>` so it survives Turbo Drive page
        navigations reliably. The body-bottom mount used to land in
        the new body after each Turbo swap, but the timing of body
        replacement vs Stimulus mutation-observer reconnects left a
        narrow window where `leader-menu` / `flat-key` controllers
        could `connect()` before `getElementById("pito-keybindings")`
        resolved against the new body's children — listener
        registration silently bailed. Head-mounted matches the same
        rationale as `pito-enroll-totp-gate` meta tag (see head
        comment above the meta): Turbo's `mergeProvisionalElements`
        diffs head children by `isEqualNode`, so identical-content
        nodes survive the merge intact. The JSON is identical on
        every page (it's a global schema) so the equality check
        keeps the same node across nav — no re-parse needed and the
        Stimulus controllers' lazy `document.getElementById`
        readers always find a populated tag. %>

    <%# D5 (2026-05-22) — leader-menu rebuild. The 1700-line nested-
        submenu / flat-key / compact-mode prior controller was retired.
        The new Tui::LeaderMenuComponent is a 1-level shallow which-key
        popup (h v g ? : q a) flowing through Tui::DialogComponent
        chrome — opened on SPACE by the tui-leader-menu Stimulus
        controller, closed on next-key commit or Esc. Mounted next to
        the help + about dialogs so the layout's `<body>`-scoped
        Stimulus controller can find `#tui-leader-menu` reliably. %>
    <%= render Tui::LeaderMenuComponent.new(screen_accent: current_section.to_sym) %>
  </body>
</html>
